//! Git Conflict Manager
//! The library is intended to solve the recurring conflict issues in git
//! The crate offers four main strategies to solve the conflict problem which are:
//! 1. Accept local: it will accept the local changes and ignore the foreign branch's changes.
//! 2. Accept Foreign: it will accept the foreign branch's changes and ignore the local changes.
//! 3. combination: it will combine both branch's changes and remove the markers (straightforward).
//!    All of which methodologies can cause a complex, diverged or broken trees in the terminal
//! Trees in git are essentials as they draw the chronological modification made on a Repository
//!    Then the commit is the stamp that provides extra more details such as the user who made the
//!    commit, time of when the commit was made and signature.
//!    Due to that, another advanced method targeted for experienced developers was introduced which
//!    is Tree Merge.
//!    Tree Merge merges the tree for either (head, foreign) branches with the past tree or the
//!    ancestor.
//!    The user get to chose the base tree (head, foreign), he also get to chose whether the
//!    interference of the past (parent) should be enabled or not.
//!    if parent interference is enabled then the current tree selected by the user is directly merged
//!    to the ancestor of the conflicted branches, resulting in a smooth straightforward tree.
//!    The method is super useful for expert developers as they don't need to worry about bucking up
//!    a specific branch if a conflict occurs, they simply chose parent interference and the branch
//!    will be merged with the changes of direct ancestor.
